SIMPLE: postil
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Postil
<hw>Pos"til</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>postille</ets>, <ets>apostille</ets>, LL. <ets>postilla</ets>,
probably from L. <ets>post illa</ets> (sc. <ets>verba</ets>) after those
(words). Cf. <er>Apostil</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, an
explanatory note in the margin of the Bible, so called because written
after the text; hence, a marginal note; a comment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Langton also made <qex>postils</qex> upon the whole Bible.</q>
<rj><qau>Foxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch. & Luth. Ch.)</fld> <def>A short homily or
commentary on a passage of Scripture; <as>as, the first <ex>postils</ex>
were composed by order of Charlemagne</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Postil
<hw>Pos"til</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>postillare</ets>.]</ety> <def>To write marginal or explanatory
notes on; to gloss.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Postil
<hw>Pos"til</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Postiled</conjf> (<?/) or <conjf>Postilled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Postiling</conjf> or
<conjf>Postilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To write postils, or marginal
notes; to comment; to postillate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Postiling</qex> and allegorizing on Scripture.</q>
<rj><qau>J. H. Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postiler</ent>⟦br⟧
